segments.text: equate that to careerism.
Short tours, I don't know why they had short tours.
And several people had several tours over there.
I don't think that a lot of them wanted to go back a second time either.
It just was, as I said before, there was nothing
There didn't seem to be anything to gain by being there.
You felt like you had your hands tied behind your back.
I don't think that our heart was in the war.
We had no motivation for the troops, and no end in sight.
You got to Vietnam right after we invaded Cambodia.
Oh, I was there when we invaded Cambodia.
Well, we were still in Cambodia.
Oh, when we invaded.
We invaded in May of 70, according to this.
You didn't get there until June of 1970.
Were you in on the invasion plan?
Are you talking about before we sent the Air Force over there?
Yes, but I mean before we sent, we didn't send any ground troops, I don't think, until I got there in the May half.
Or maybe it was just before I got there.
It may have been.
You may be right.
Well, as far as the camp,
I thought it was pretty successful.
I really did.
Air Force had a problem because we had all these temples and things that we weren't supposed to bomb.
And we had to send out pictures of all of them and tell them you can't bomb this and you can't bomb that.
And if you see one of these in your sight when you're on a run, you pull out, you don't do it.
Because we were afraid of the cultural.
trying to protect the cultural items that were there.
Temples, most of them are temples.
Buddhist temples and statues and that kind of thing.
Well, of course, this is that whole conflict between culture and war.
And what was your opinion?
Well, I didn't see any reason to destroy it.
Of course, the Vietnamese, if they knew that, they'd just go get in the place.
But I think we broke up their playoff, in a fair speaking.
Did you get much time off in Saigon?
I didn't go to Saigon, but once or twice.
Because you were working too hard or because you just didn't want to go?
I just didn't have time.
And that was to visit.
the headquarters of the Special Forces for briefing one of them, I was relieved.
I never made a...
I never made a visit for pleasure that downtown was going down while I was there.
I had no desire to go anywhere.
I went there for Special Forces briefing.
And I went there to... for a...
A guy who had worked for me through training Air Force was out of the service and was over there working for some commercial airline.
And he invited me over to his house once.
And that's the only time I was there.
Now, one of the problems in Vietnam by 1970 is that the US Army reported that 50%
The enlisted troops in the Army were using marijuana.
Did you have any problems like that in the Air Force?
Yes.
We had problems like that, and it wasn't as large as that.
I don't think we had it near that size of a problem.
We did have a problem there.
I wasn't as familiar with that as
I didn't get much information on that except the staff meeting.
What did the Air Force say about it at the staff meetings?
Well, there was a problem and they had a screening, they had a urine screening test they were getting done, but they left to go home and treated them if they needed to.
Occasionally they would catch one and court-martial him.
But apparently marijuana was very easy to come by.
Especially in downtown Saigon.
I was wondering about something else.

In the United States, by, of course, the invasion of Cambodia, Kansas State, and all these things in the summer of 1970, and even before there, there was a growing anti-war protest movement in America.
Did that have an impact on the war?
Well, that's hard to say.
Because I don't know what impact it had on the soldiers or the airmen or whoever was over in uniform, the individuals.
What about as far as you were concerned, the Tanzanute?
Did it ever have any impact?
You must have read about these things.
Oh, I read about it, and we saw it on television.
But I am so conservative that I resented it.
And I thought the people were unpatriotic.
I still do.
And I don't condone it in any way, shape, or form.
It's just foreign to my nature.
And what did your, I mean, you must have seen these things on, I didn't realize you
Well, it was Armed Forces TV.
It's a closed circuit there that they had on, they put on, they run them on Armed Forces TV.
They had a closed circuit television.
I guess you could get the things over to somewhere.
I guess it must have a video tape.
Sure.
I could be out of date, but it would be more up to date in the newspapers.
You must have seen this with other officers.
Did you ever discuss this with other officers at Tansanoo?
Oh, yeah.
What did they have to say?
They felt like I did.
There may be a reason for stopping the war, but that was not a good reason.
Of course, we had all sworn to upheld the Constitution and obey the Commander-in-Chief.
Sure.
We felt like they should, they should too.
Wow.
I know your opinion has been on some of these controversial issues.
You stayed there for six months.
Were you happy or sad to leave?
Well, of course, you're always happy to leave a war zone.
I would have liked to have stayed a little longer.
I didn't...
I felt like I could contribute some more, but if it felt like somebody else could contribute more, that's fine.
And when you left, did you think that we were going to win that war?
No.
I didn't see any way we could win it.
Unless they turned us loose, turned the Air Force loose.
Probably could have obliterated them.
And all that.
That might have stopped it.
No matter what.
They weren't going to lose today.
Did you resent the fact that they weren't going to let you use your full force?
Yes.
Sure did.
Okay, you left there in January of 1971.
And you retired at the end of that year.
And you just made Major General a year before, but before we talk about why you retired, I'd like to talk about your last duty assignment.
It was only 10 months from January 71 to October 71.
You were the assistant to the commander.
I can't read that.
Aerospace Defense Command.
Aerospace Defense Command.
That's out in Colorado Springs.
Oh.
What did you do out there?
Well, I was the assistant to the commander, and we manned the command post in Cheyenne Mountain.
And they had charge of all the air defense and all the monitor.
The tunnel, the one underneath the mountain?
Yeah, in Cheyenne Mountain.
And we monitored all the space objects, the whole space program, everything in space.
We kept track of everything.
That must have been pretty interesting.
It was a new command, something totally new for you.
Well, no, I'd been in air defense before.
But, I mean, monitoring that.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, it was a completely new experience.
We kept count of all the space garbage and everything that was in space.
So to keep up with what the Soviets had and what we had.
Yeah, everything.
Kept up with everything in space.
And monitored from monitoring tracking stations all over the world.
Had big radars over in England, up in Alaska, and out in the islands.
and down in Florida, we've been in several more big ones all over the world.
All that information's funneled in, and it's all computer-handled, and you can pick up the situation at any time.
At the commander's position, you can pick up the situation all over the world of what's going on in space.
command and control system set up, alternate command and control for the Air Force.
It's a real interesting mission.
It is fascinating.
big appreciation for what all is going on in space because there's a lot more going on than I had any idea of.
For example?
Just all the different, all the garbage that's up there, and they wait until they all burn out before they stop tracking them.
All the so-called spy satellites?
Yep.
I've seen some of the pictures that we have of Cuba and some other parts that we've taken on satellites, and I'm always amazed.
Well, they have high resolution cameras.
And did you analyze those pictures or did you send them out to?
Oh, the intelligence people do that.
Did you send them out to DIA?
Well, they go through intelligence channels.
I don't know where all they are.
through the Defense Intelligence Agency.
Was your headquarters right in that mountain itself?
No, the headquarters itself was down in downtown Kellogg Springs.
They call it Camp Air Force Base, which is just the compound of the building.
Inside the mountain, what do they have?
pretty much the command post for air defense in case of an attack?
Yes.
That's where the Army anti-aircraft and missiles are controlled from there.
That's where Commander Norrand, that's his command post.
Commander North American Defense Command.
Why did you only stay there for 10 months?
I retired to get into this business.
Why did you?
So in other words, you just made major general.
Do you think there was a possibility for another promotion?
Well, I was getting close to my retirement date, and I doubted I'd get promoted before my retirement date.
When was your retirement date?
Was it 73 then?
No, I had constructive service on top of what I had.
It was probably 72.
So you didn't think that you'd make Lieutenant General?
I guess I found my level of incompetence, that's what they say.
Find your level of incompetence and quit.
Incompetence.
Now, why did you retire?
To get into this business.
And did you have an opportunity to take over this business at that time?
Or did you build this from the ground up?
I mean, you were explaining before.
My uncle had this company.
He offered myself and Bon Jackson, another man who had been working for him for 40 years.
So we were in the process of buying him out.
And this man decided he wanted to retire too.
And also R.C.
's son-in-law owns some stock.
And L.H.
bought that stock from the son-in-law.
And then after Mr. Jackson retired, we bought his stock.
And then we decided to let this other guy in, and we're selling some stock to him.
There'll be three of us in the bed.
You had pretty firm plans about civilian life.
I didn't until this came.
He had called me to come visit him in August, and I retired in November.
You had spent an entire career in the military.
What were your feelings when you retired?
Well, I was a little sad, but
I was looking forward to a new career, a new challenge.
I certainly got it.
But we built the company up, the three of us, from a relatively small volume up to a much larger volume of business.
I don't know if we're making any money or not, but we're getting a lot of work done, a lot more work done.
And we've gone from about 50 employees up to 135.
So we feel like we've made some progress.
It hasn't all been easy, though.
Some of the jobs have been terrible.
We just hope we have enough good jobs to offset all the terrible ones.
Now let's talk about how people advance in the military.
You went, you had many advancements, and I'd like to know your opinions on some of these questions.
Do people advance in the military because, in general, because being at the right place?
Well, I think it's a combination of both.
The job that you do is very important, and it's written up as such.
But what was it?
You also have to say, what was it that he did?
What was the level of this accomplishment?
And if you get a good job, and you do a good job, you're more likely to get promoted than even if you do an outstanding job and a poor job.
And you're in competition with your peers.
I guess a lot of it depends on how well your boss can cite your accomplishments.
And then a lot of it depends on who gets to read your file on the promotion board because it's an enormous number they have to look at and how they rate them.
And the system they have, I think, is quite fair.
But all you can look at is the guy's picture and what's written on paper.
That's all you have to do, unless you happen to know him personally.
But does that help, knowing somebody personally?
Does that help?
It might help, and it might hurt.
Well, if you did a good job.
Yeah.
If you've done a good job for someone sitting on the board, that will help.
But it's very unlikely that the guy that you know will even see your record, though.
When you were in the military, did you consider yourself ambitious?
Relatively so, yeah.
I was highly motivated, and I guess that means ambitious.
I wanted to succeed, yes.
Did you want to, when you were a younger man, did you want to become a general?
Yes.
That was always my goal.
Now, does someone become a leader in the armed forces in a similar way that they become a leader in professional or in business life?
Now, you had 10 years here of experience in
successful because of the same, I mean, do you get ahead the same way in this last 10 years that you did in the previous almost 30 years?
Well, I haven't exerted as much leadership in this business as I did in the military, in no way, shape, or form.
Because I wasn't
I didn't exert as much leadership when I came in this business, and certainly not as much as I do now.
And I've gotten a reputation in the business so that now I have been given a position of leadership in the industry.
But as far as the company is concerned, it's been different.
As far as leadership is concerned, do you leave people, your workers here, like leave them in the military?
No.
Can you tell me the differences?
The people here are not as motivated.
It's very difficult to get people now who really want to work.
They want a position with a salary, but no work.
And the few old-timers that we have left are the only ones that really want to work and do work.
And the younger people work when they want to.
That's the way it appears to me.
So you think it's easier to wait in the military than it is out here in civilian life?
Yes, very definitely.
Do you think the ranking system has anything to do with that?
No, because you have a ranking system.
Sure.
You've got workers, then you've got foremen, then you've got superintendents, right on up the ladder.
It's very difficult to motivate workers when you have just a few workers at each place and you're scattered all over East Texas.
And you're so dependent, so dependent on the people under you.
And they, of course, are not highly trained.
Sure.
Most of them haven't even finished high school.
What duty station did you like the most in your military career?
From what standpoint?
From a duty standpoint?
Yeah, which one did you like the most?
Which one did you find the most satisfying?
Maxwell is common on the squadron officers because I get more satisfaction out of that.
Do you think that that's the place that was your greatest accomplishment?
Perhaps.
I feel like I made a contribution to a lot of young Air Force officers.
I helped them get us
a comprehension of where they wanted to go and what they wanted to do.
What about one that you thought was the least contribution?
That was much more of a frustration.
I was perhaps Korea.
Very frustrating.
Why?
Didn't seem like we had a mission.
I mean, you don't have a mission.
We did have a mission, but it really wasn't much.
Some people have said that there's a military way to do something.
And you read about this every once in a while in the paper.
Is there a military mentality or a military mind, in your opinion?
Not as a category, no.
You'll find in the military as diverse as the same as if you own that, even that, if you live in Australia.
You can have hard-headed,
obnoxious people in the military and you have part of obnoxious people in civilian life.
And I don't think that you can lay all that on a military mentality or a military mind.
I think by and large the people in the military that I've known is the same as people outside of
Some guys get ahead and some guys don't.
Some guys are motivated and some guys aren't.
Okay.
Let's go to leadership.
We sort of talked around leadership, but we've never really defined it.
Would you define it for me?
What's leadership to you?
Well, I would define leadership as getting people to do in a willing way what you want them to do and like it.
How do you do that?
I wish I knew all the answers.
Well, you've got to create the desire first.
Once you've created the desire, then the willingness follows.
And they do what you want them to.
What kind of values do leaders have?
I'd say as diverse as you can find.
There are so many different leaders.
Types of leaders.
Types of leaders that have been successful that I would not attempt to put them in a mold.
Eisenhower and MacArthur were poles apart, personality and motivation and everything else.
Winston Churchill is another completely different person.
He was a great leader.
patent for all his faults, I thought was a great leader, because he got the people to do things willingly.
Accomplishments where he did some things that I think were atrocious.
For example?
He slapped a soldier down in Italy.
He wheeled around with pearl-antle pistols on his belt.
Showmanship.
But
He was highly respected by his men.
They may have hated his guts, but they respected him and they willingly did what he asked them to.
What kind of leader were you?
Well, I tried to lead by example.
I always had people about me that
that wanted to do what I wanted them to do.
The success I had, of course, was due to their assistance.
So you thought that one aspect of leadership was choosing the best amount?
I think the important aspect of it.
I think you'll find that most successful leaders pick the men that are around them.
Or they find somebody that's there that they trust, and they get his support.
I think the establishment of an esprit de corps within the unit is a very important aspect of leadership.
You've got to have something.
I don't care if it's a gimmick.
To get them together and focusing on what it is you're trying to do.
You've got to put the mission first.
Everybody's got to know what it is.
What they're trying to do is pretend they've been all going towards it.
I think the leader's got to furnish that sort of guidance.
And I think that the leader's got to know what's going on.
and he gets all the help he can.
We've had a lot of changes at Texas A&M over the last 20 years, and certainly since you were there.
Did you ever happen to know General Earl Rudder was the president?
I certainly did.
What was your opinion of the general?
I loved the man.
I knew him when he was football coach at John Tarleton when I was at A&M.
And I saw him several times up there when I visited.
I was still a student at A&M.
I also saw him in Europe before D-Day in London.
And I saw him many times after that when he was president of A&M.
I visited there a few times and talked to him.
I didn't see him several times.
What was it that you loved about him?
He was a guy that set the example.
He could motivate people.
And he could get people to do what he wanted them to do,
He was a good man.
A real fine person.
During his
years at A&M in 1960 there were a lot of very controversial changes that I'd like to ask you about.
One was that they ended the mandatory affiliation with the Corps of Cadets and now
I think it was inevitable, unless the school or university wanted to stay small.
I really do.
I thought the school was a closer-knit school when that was the case, but with the growth in population and the education requirement, I think it was inevitable.
especially with the anti-military sentiment and so forth that's going, that's around.
It wasn't ever.
What about allowing women to go to A&M?
I feel the same way about that.
I think we've already discussed that a little, but we already have women at West Point and the area.
I think society has changed and the time came.
What about allowing blacks to go to A&M?
It was integrated in 1968.
Well, I think it should have been done before that.
We had Puerto Ricans, we had Mexicans, we had everything else.
I think qualified students should be allowed, regardless of race, color, or creed, anywhere.
I was wondering about the drought, your ideas about the drought.
Do you think we should reinstitute a drought?
I think we owe it to universal suffrage, not universal suffrage, but universal military training or equivalent, peace corps or otherwise.
But I think it would restore some semblance of discipline to this country.
It's gone to pot in my opinion now.
All our mowers are relaxed, so we almost have nothing.
We're degenerate, almost degenerate.
If we're not degenerate, we're damn near that right now.
And you think that by inducting men into the services of health hands?
You teach people a little self-discipline, at least some, and make a contribution to society.
A lot of them were never made.
What about drafting, or in your universal military system, what about inducting women?
How do you feel on that?
Well, I think the same for women as for men.
So you think that we should draft women?
Yes.
I don't think we ought to draft them for combat, but I think we ought to draft them for support roles or some form of contribution to the betterment of society.
I mentioned the Peace Corps, but the Peace Corps is just one thing.
There are other things that could be that can be worked out.
I think that they could be used in many different ways.
But they would be forced to do this just through a strict discipline.
I think perhaps my generation has made a mistake
And that's the reason we have, maybe the reason we have what we have now, because we gave our kids everything.
They never had to work for a thing.
Because we had to work.
We didn't want them to have to go through that.
So you think that the parents of the 50s and 60s were too easy on their children?
Gave them everything.
They never had to work for a thing.
Because they had to work so hard in the Depression.
Well, we couldn't afford an ice cream cone now.
We give them anything they want.
I think we're feeling the effects of it.
I know that even though my dad paid my tuition to college, I still worked every summer to make enough money to survive otherwise.
He paid whatever the fee was for my board tuition and board, but everything else I paid for myself.
I didn't have a car.
I didn't own a car until after I got through the war.
I owned half a car once.
After I graduated from West Point, I owned half a car.
I'm wondering about the recent tendency in the Armed Forces
You sort of alluded to this, but I'd like a direct answer.
In the armed forces, toward increasing the number of duty billets that women perform.
For example, now we have women pilots in the Air Force.
What's your opinion of that?
We had women pilots in World War II.
But not as many as we have now.
Well, I know not as many as now, but they flew ferried aircraft.
And now they're going into cruise.
And there's no reason why a woman can't fly an airplane just as well as a man.
They can drive a car just as well as a man.
And there's not a gross amount of difference between driving a car safely and just flying an airplane.
You only have two problems in an airplane.
It's takeoff and landing that's real problems.
Problem time.
And an automobile, you've got it at every intersection.
And so you support increasing the role of women in the service?
Yes, I sure do.
Okay, fine.
And did you, when you were in the military, this is a little bit before the big increase of women, but did you have any duty stations in which you had a lot of women in which you worked?
For example, some of the students at the schools and anything like that, there probably weren't very many women working.
When I was Secretary of the Air University, I had a girl working for me.
She was, that was in her fifties, and she was pretty good.
What about the students?
We had not had many students, girls students, since the time I left.
female officer for?
We had a few female officers, that's all.
But they had not started going to the...
Yes, they had.
We got, by the time I left, we had a few girls come in to squadron officer school.
Either that or right after I left, because I can remember deciding what we would do if we did get girls.
How would you handle them?
They played athletics and everything else just like everybody else.
We tried to treat them exactly the same.
Any problems?
No.
They're built different.
Yeah, we know that.
I'm at about the end of my questions.
But I'm not the expert on your life.
Maybe there's something that I've missed.
Maybe there's something about your career
Well, I think we got off base, and we tried to do all things for everybody.
Trying to correct inequities of centuries of abuse by legislating the money to do it, and that one helped one bit.
I think it's already been proved that it hasn't helped.
It may have helped some individuals financially, but that's all.
It hasn't helped.
